00:00:00.014 --> 00:00:01.430
LINDSAY METCALFE:
Hello, everyone,

00:00:01.430 --> 00:00:04.210
and welcome to our talk
"Designing for Daydream."

00:00:04.210 --> 00:00:07.640
How many people here
attended a VR talk yesterday?

00:00:07.640 --> 00:00:08.970
It's really great to see this.

00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:11.660
It's so nice to see so many
people who have been designing

00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:14.760
VR for a while, and who are just
really excited about everything

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:16.790
we're doing here at IO, and
then people who are just getting

00:00:16.790 --> 00:00:17.290
started.

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:23.720
So for Daydream,
our goal here is

00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:26.366
enabling very high
quality mobile VR,

00:00:26.366 --> 00:00:28.490
all the way from like
hardware up through the stock

00:00:28.490 --> 00:00:29.800
to the user experience.

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:31.990
So we really want to make
sure that we're giving you

00:00:31.990 --> 00:00:34.830
everything that you need to
create really compelling VR

00:00:34.830 --> 00:00:36.029
immersive experiences.

00:00:36.029 --> 00:00:38.070
And we've talked a lot
this week about everything

00:00:38.070 --> 00:00:41.640
from hardware optimizations
to developer tools.

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:43.510
And we had some great
talks yesterday too.

00:00:43.510 --> 00:00:46.640
So yesterday we talked
about VR filmmaking.

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:48.610
We had a really
great talk on lessons

00:00:48.610 --> 00:00:52.060
learned from design labs from
our rapid prototyping team.

00:00:52.060 --> 00:00:54.150
And you can watch all
of this on YouTube

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:56.450
if you missed any of this.

00:00:56.450 --> 00:00:58.830
And so today we want to go
a bit deeper in designing

00:00:58.830 --> 00:01:01.520
for Daydream and talk all
about the key ingredients

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:04.019
and considerations for
designing for Daydream.

00:01:04.019 --> 00:01:06.470
So really, what's
important for creating

00:01:06.470 --> 00:01:08.740
great VR content
that's comfortable,

00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:10.495
engaging but also unique?

00:01:10.495 --> 00:01:12.620
And to do this we're going
to walk you through four

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:13.720
different lightning talks.

00:01:16.569 --> 00:01:18.860
So the first of these, at
the center of the experience,

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:20.700
we're going to take a
look at your audience.

00:01:20.700 --> 00:01:22.230
So who are you designing for ?

00:01:22.230 --> 00:01:24.300
What do we know
about them already?

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:26.260
And what of that
can help you create

00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:28.102
the very best content for them?

00:01:28.102 --> 00:01:30.310
And then we're going to take
a look at the ergonomics

00:01:30.310 --> 00:01:31.770
of that user in VR.

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:34.390
So what are the important
considerations and constraints

00:01:34.390 --> 00:01:36.600
that can give you a
starting point for designing

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:37.460
and prototyping.

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:39.780
In VR?

00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:41.586
Next, creating a
feeling of presence

00:01:41.586 --> 00:01:43.960
and being able to transport
people to different realities

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:45.714
is really key to grafting VR.

00:01:45.714 --> 00:01:47.130
So we're going to
talk you through

00:01:47.130 --> 00:01:49.260
why crafting the right
environment is important,

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:51.209
and also how to get it right.

00:01:51.209 --> 00:01:53.250
And then finally, we're
to explore something else

00:01:53.250 --> 00:01:56.180
that's also really important
for presence, which is input,

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:58.060
and how you can use a
world of interactions

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:00.357
that are made possible with
our Daydream controller.

00:02:00.357 --> 00:02:02.190
And now I'm going to
hand this over to Dave,

00:02:02.190 --> 00:02:04.140
and he's going to talk to
you about your audience.

00:02:04.140 --> 00:02:05.000
Thank you so much.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:10.460
